    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Before suburban streets, Northdale sat on a 1,300‑acre cattle ranch once owned by Walter Wyman 'Willie' Ragg Sr.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/northdale_florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The Northdale Golf & Tennis Club opened its 18‑hole, 6,824‑yard championship course in 1979, becoming a centerpiece for early residents.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3,
        26
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/northdale_florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "In the mid‑1970s, developer Bob Sierra built affordable single‑family homes for mid‑$30,000s to high $50,000s, shaping Northdale’s early community.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        25
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/northdale_florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "In 1977, two historic log cabins were moved to fields beside modern Lake Shore Drive, preserving the Ragg family legacy.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/northdale_florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "During the 1940s, the Nichols family ran a dairy farm on the 1,300 acres that would become Northdale, highlighting its agrarian past.",
